        <h2>Why Most Nutrition Apps Miss the Mark for Older Adults</h2>
        <p>Walk through the top nutrition apps on the App Store and you'll notice something: they're all trying to do everything. Calories. Macros. Micros. Water intake. Sleep. Exercise. Barcode scanning. Meal planning. Weekly reports. Premium upgrades.</p>
        <p>That feature arms race makes sense for the apps' core demographic — younger adults managing complex fitness goals who enjoy the data. It does not make sense for a 55-year-old man whose single objective is to make sure he's eating enough protein to hold onto the muscle mass he's spent a lifetime building.</p>
        <p>For that person, every extra screen is friction. Every upsell is an interruption. Every barcode scan is a reminder that the app wasn't built for him.</p>
        <p>You don't need more features. You need fewer steps.</p>
        <p>The research on habit formation is unambiguous: the harder a behavior is to perform, the less likely it becomes automatic. Complexity is the enemy of consistency. And for adults over 40 trying to build a sustainable protein habit, consistency is the whole game.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>The feature paradox</h3>
          <p>More features don't make tracking easier — they make it harder. The apps with the highest long-term user retention aren't the most comprehensive ones. They're the ones that match the tool to the actual goal. <strong>If your goal is protein, your app should be about protein.</strong></p>
        </div>
      </div>

