        <h2>How Much Protein Should Older Adults Be Tracking Toward?</h2>
        <p>The target varies by bodyweight, but the principle is consistent: older adults need significantly more protein than the standard government recommendation, which was designed to prevent deficiency — not to preserve muscle mass during aging.</p>
        <p>Research supports 1.2–1.6 grams of protein per kilogram of bodyweight per day for adults over 40. For most men, that translates to 100–140 grams daily — roughly double the RDA. The specific number goes up slightly as you age, since anabolic resistance (your muscles' declining sensitivity to protein) increases through the 50s and 60s.</p>
        <p>The gap between what most men are eating and what the research recommends is 30–50 grams per day. That gap is invisible without tracking — which is exactly why the habit matters.</p>

